<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>🎢 005 Week 3 — English Worksheet (Intermediate)</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Amenities — Functions Calling Functions · <strong>Course:</strong> Theme Park Creator · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>Your park has stalls. Now it needs <strong>amenities</strong> — a <strong>bathroom</strong>, a <strong>janitor room</strong>.</p>
<p>Both are rooms. So you write <strong>one</strong> <code>build_room</code> helper. Both amenity functions <strong>call</strong> it, then add their own fitting.</p>
<p>These are the blocks you use this week:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">blocks.fill(QUARTZ_BLOCK, pos(0, 0, 0), pos(4, 3, 4), FillOperation.HOLLOW)
blocks.fill(AIR, pos(2, 1, 0), pos(2, 2, 0), FillOperation.REPLACE)
blocks.place(CAULDRON, pos(1, 1, 1))
</code></pre>
<blockquote>
<p><code>blocks.fill(material, corner1, corner2, ...)</code> fills a box between two corners.
<code>FillOperation.HOLLOW</code> = outer <strong>walls</strong> only — the middle is <strong>cleared to air</strong>.
<code>FillOperation.REPLACE</code> = the <strong>whole solid</strong> box.
<code>blocks.place(block, pos(x, y, z))</code> puts <strong>one</strong> block in <strong>one</strong> spot.
<code>CAULDRON</code> = the toilet. <code>BARREL</code> = the janitor's supplies.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Meet Helper Functions 🧰</h2>
<p>A <strong>helper function</strong> does one job. Other functions <strong>call</strong> it instead of writing that job again.</p>
<pre><code class="language-text">   build_bathroom(5)            build_janitor_room(4)
        │                            │
        ├─▶ build_room(...)          ├─▶ build_room(...)   ← ONE helper
        │                            │
        └─▶ place CAULDRON           └─▶ place BARREL
</code></pre>
<p>Here is the helper. It builds walls, a floor, and a doorway:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def build_room(wall, floor, size):
    blocks.fill(wall, pos(0, 0, 0), pos(size, 3, size), FillOperation.HOLLOW)
    blocks.fill(floor, pos(0, 0, 0), pos(size, 0, size), FillOperation.REPLACE)
    blocks.fill(AIR, pos(2, 1, 0), pos(2, 2, 0), FillOperation.REPLACE)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Why is writing <code>build_room</code> once better than writing those three fills in both amenity functions?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each function. Write what you think happens.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def build_bathroom(size):
    build_room(QUARTZ_BLOCK, STONE, size)
    blocks.place(CAULDRON, pos(1, 1, 1))

build_bathroom(5)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What are the walls made of? What is the floor made of? How wide is the room?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">def build_janitor_room(size):
    build_room(OAK_PLANKS, STONE, size)
    blocks.place(BARREL, pos(1, 1, 1))

build_janitor_room(4)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Both amenities call the same helper. What is different about the two rooms?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block is broken. Read what it should do, rewrite it so it works, then explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — This should build a bathroom: a room, then a cauldron. But only a <strong>lonely cauldron</strong> appears, with no room around it.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def build_bathroom(size):
    blocks.place(CAULDRON, pos(1, 1, 1))

build_bathroom(5)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the helper exists, but nobody calls it.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — This should give the bathroom <strong>quartz walls</strong> and a <strong>stone floor</strong>. But the walls come out stone and the floor comes out quartz.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def build_bathroom(size):
    build_room(STONE, QUARTZ_BLOCK, size)
    blocks.place(CAULDRON, pos(1, 1, 1))

build_bathroom(5)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the helper's parameters are <code>(wall, floor, size)</code>. Arguments land in those boxes <strong>by position</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — This should build a room with a cauldron inside. The room appears, but the <strong>cauldron is gone</strong>.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def build_bathroom(size):
    blocks.place(CAULDRON, pos(1, 1, 1))
    build_room(QUARTZ_BLOCK, STONE, size)

build_bathroom(5)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> <code>FillOperation.HOLLOW</code> clears the middle of the room to air. The cauldron is in the middle.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Build the Amenities 🚻</h2>
<p>In your homework world, write <strong>one</strong> helper and <strong>two</strong> functions that call it:</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">def build_room(wall, floor, size):
def build_bathroom(size):
def build_janitor_room(size):
</code></pre>
<p><code>build_room</code> builds:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>walls</strong> from the <code>wall</code> material with <code>FillOperation.HOLLOW</code></li>
<li>a <strong>floor</strong> from the <code>floor</code> material</li>
<li>a <strong>doorway</strong> carved with <code>AIR</code> so a visitor can walk in</li>
</ul>
<p><code>build_bathroom</code> calls <code>build_room</code>, then places a <code>CAULDRON</code> inside.
<code>build_janitor_room</code> calls <code>build_room</code> with different materials, then places a <code>BARREL</code> inside.</p>
<p>Neither amenity function has a <code>blocks.fill</code> of its own. The walls, floor and doorway all come from the helper.</p>
<p>Run <code>build_bathroom(5)</code>. Then <strong>walk somewhere new</strong> and run <code>build_janitor_room(4)</code>, so the two rooms stand apart.</p>
<p><strong>Write your helper and your two amenity functions:</strong></p>
